That saying is blunt, but there’s a very practical engineering lesson behind it.

The lesson isn’t about the wording—it’s about utility density.

Every item in your ruck had to justify its weight. If something only solved one narrow problem, it had better solve that problem so exceptionally well that carrying it was worth the cost.

That’s a good systems principle:

Every dependency has a carrying cost.

Whether it’s code, equipment, employees, or beliefs.

So, “worthiness” has become an interesting question.

To me, worthiness isn’t about deserving admiration or moral perfection.

It’s closer to earning your place within a constrained system.

A thing is worthy when the value it consistently creates exceeds the cost of keeping it around.

Different domains express that differently.

* In engineering: high signal, low complexity.
* In biology: contributes more energy than it consumes over the long term.
* In economics: creates durable value.
* In a team: increases the capability of the group.
* In software: removes more bugs than it introduces.
* In a backpack: earns its ounces.
* In a story: advances the narrative.
* In a friendship: leaves both people better than before.

Notice what’s common:

Worth isn’t static.

It’s relational.

It’s contextual.

It’s demonstrated over time.

