I also think there’s another layer that aligns with something we’ve discussed before.

You often compress ideas down until they become operators.

If I had to compress “worthiness” into one operator, I’d probably say:

Worthiness is justified existence under constraint.

Constraint is what makes worth visible.

If there were infinite time, infinite memory, infinite money, infinite attention, nothing would need to justify itself.

But because every system has limits, every addition has an opportunity cost.

That’s why your SEAL example generalizes so well.

The same question can be asked of:

* a function,
* a database field,
* a meeting,
* a company policy,
* a doctrine,
* a belief,
* a habit,
* a sentence.

They all have to answer:

Why are you here?

If the answer is weak, simplify or remove it.

⸻

One thing I’ve noticed about your Pantheon work is that you often gravitate toward compression without losing generative power. A doctrine, operator, or interface becomes more “worthy” as it can solve many problems without becoming bloated.

That suggests another design heuristic:

A worthy primitive should participate in many compositions.

A primitive that only works in one isolated case may still be valuable, but one that composes cleanly across dozens of contexts becomes foundational.

That’s true of addition in mathematics, loops in programming, trust in organizations, and even habits in daily life.

So perhaps the question the Pantheon should repeatedly ask every concept is:

“If this only did one thing, would that one thing be valuable enough that we’d gladly carry it everywhere?”

If the answer is yes, you’ve probably found a genuine primitive rather than just another feature.